observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to require the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer to:
coordinate with the BAC on the prompt scheduling of procurements activities of PPAs included in the LDRRMFIP;

monitor the implementation of the programs, projects and activities (PPA);

coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in the preparation of the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to ensure that disbursements are in accordance with the approved LDRRMFIP; and

submit the required Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to the Municipal Accountant for onward submission on or before the 15th day after end of each month to the Audit Team pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories at least once a year and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record all regularly procured supplies and materials to the appropriate inventory accounts following the perpetual inventory method and prepare SLCs for supplies and materials by type/class;
Require the GSO to maintain Supplies Cards (SCs) for supplies and materials by type/class and prepare and submit the RSMI based on consolidated RIS to the Municipal Accountant within five days after the end of the month and the RSMI shall be the basis in drawing a JV to record the issuance; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to draw the JV based on the RSMI to record the issuance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require MDRRMO to ensure implementation of the Programs, Projects and Other Activities for the LDRRMF and monitor its implementation;
Require the BAC on the scheduling of the procurement activities of PPAs included in the LDRRMFIP;
Remind the Municipal Accountant to transfer all unexpended/unobligated balance of the 30% Quick Response Fund and the70% Mitigation Fund   to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liabilities – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund” (account number 2-04-01-020) in the Trust Fund Book; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to verify the variances between the Report on the Utilization of DRRMFand the amount presented in the Notes to Financial Statements and to make the necessary corrections in the balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Direct the MDRRMO to submit a complete list of recipients for the distribution of welfare goods to households for verification;
Direct the MDRRMO, Rural Health Office and other departments in-charge of the front liners to submit the attendance sheets of front liners who received the food items from the caterer indicating therein their name, work schedule and signature for further evaluation on the validity of payment of catering services;
Require the Municipal Accountant to make sure that complete data must be provided in the supporting documents attached to disbursements vouchers such as Purchase Orders, Acceptance and Inspection Report, etc. before these are forwarded to the Municipal Treasurer for payment; and
Require the GSO to account for the difference between the goods procured and distributed.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:
Require the Members of the Sangguniang Bayan to enact an ordinance to augment any item in the approved budget for their respective offices from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations;
Determine first the estimated needed funds of PPAs before realignment so funds can be optimally utilized for more necessary expenses of the municipality;
Require the Municipal Health Officer to submit a list of  quarantined LSIs, ROFs indicating duration of quarantine period and certified by the Rural Health Unit/Officer and submit attendance sheets of assigned medical health workers and frontliners on duty with signature acknowledging receipt of meals;
Require the MDRMO to submit  list of beneficiaries/recepients with signature acknowledging receipt of    the  welfare goods distributed consisting of 500 sacks of rice and 4,110 kilos of Bangus; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to verify completeness of data in the supporting documents attached to disbursements vouchers such as Purchase Requests, Purchase Orders, and Inspection & Acceptance Reports, etc. before these are forwarded to the Municipal Treasurer for payment.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
require the Municipal Accountant to determine the cost of the road lot and recognize it as part of the road network component including the cost of constructing the drainage and slope protection and other miscellaneous structure, if there is any;
cause the creation of an Inventory Committee and require the Committee to conduct an inventory of all the local roads under its jurisdiction, prepare and submit a verified Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;

require the General Services Officer, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile their respective records; and,

require the Municipal Accountant to maintain and update subsidiary ledgers. and disclose in the notes to financial statements the local road network system as prescribed by regulation.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to require the Municipal Accountant:
to conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of fund transfers;

to reconcile the unliquidated fund transfers with the source agencies and prepare adjusting entries for the reconciling items noted, and require liquidation of the balances.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayorto require the Municipal Treasurer and the TOMWASA General Manager Designate:
to monitor the monthly collections of the billed water consumption for the Office and take proper action on non-paying consumers;
to issue demand letters to delinquent water service concessionaires and exercise the right to disconnect service lines for reasons of failure to comply with the demand letter within the stipulated period.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor and to the Local Sanggunian:
a. to craft ordinances and issue executive orders related to waste management and environmental protection;

b. to strengthen the current waste management system of the Municipality, including, garbage classification, collection, and recycling;to add more waste recycling facilities; andto focus on the recycling methods of the recyclables.
